Executive Summary 
Operations in Low Earth Orbit (LEO) face persistent challenges related to spacecraft orientation, 
microgravity disturbances, and the lack of standardized long-tether deployment systems. Maintaining stable 
alignment between spacecraft is especially difficult without a mechanism capable of controlling tension, 
dissipating static charge, and reliably deploying a long conductive tether. Current industry solutions do not 
offer compact, CubeSat-sized architectures that can store, release, and monitor a tether while keeping the 
system mechanically reliable and electrically grounded. This project addresses those gaps by developing an 
integrated tether deployment system designed specifically for small satellite platforms. 
The challenge defined by Summanus Aerospace is to design a compact tether system for two 12U 
SmallSats, weighing 24 kg each, that allows them to rotate about their common center of mass to simulate 
lunar (0.166 g) or Martian (0.38 g) gravity. To support such maneuvers, the system must deploy 50вАУ150 meters 
of tether wire, maintain controlled tension, dissipate electrostatic charge, and operate reliably for a minimum 
of six months in the LEO thermal environment. All hardware must fit within a 2U or 3U volume, conform to the 
CubeSat Design Specification, and integrate with standard 6061/7075 aluminum frames. 
The Talon Tether is a complete response to this design challenge. It is a compact tether deployment and 
charge-management system built around a 3UвАУ1U dual-satellite architecture. The 3U frame on the mother 
satellite houses the mechanical deployment system consisting of the reel and level wind subsystems, while 
the 1U frame on the daughter satellite includes the tether attachment subsystem to secure and monitor the 
tether wire and the electron emitter subsystem to keep the satellites electrically grounded. The Talon Tether 
was engineered to maintain stable tension, manage electrodynamic effects, operate continuously in LEOвАЩs 
вИТ40¬∞C to +80¬∞C temperature regime, and comply with mass and volume constraints while providing longduration operational reliability. 
At the heart of the product is the reel subsystem, which stores and deploys the tether using a stepper motor 
for precise rotational control. The motor meshes with the right reel mount, and the drive shaft fits into a D hole 
on the right side of the spool. This connection allows the motor to drive the rotation of the spool. The left side 
of the spool features a spur gear with 40 teeth that rotates around a ball bearing on the left reel mount to 
minimize friction and ensure smooth, consistent rotation. Additionally, there is an M5 8-millimeter screw that 
threads into the left side of the spool. A 5 mm hole is drilled above where the screw is threaded, and the end of 
the tether wire is fed through this hole and wrapped around the screw so that it always remains secured. A 
microservo-driven mechanical lock provides an emergency brake capable of instantly halting spool motion in 
off-nominal conditions, supporting safe deployment, fault protection, and tension control. 
To prevent tangling, bunching, or uneven layering of the tether wire, the product incorporates a 
mechanically synchronized level wind subsystem. This assembly uses a smaller spur gear meshed with the 
spoolвАЩs left side gear to drive the rotation of a bidirectional threaded rod. A sliding carriage translates along the 
rod as the spool rotates, guiding the wire into evenly distributed layers. This subsystem enables high-density 
storage in a restricted CubeSat volume while ensuring repeatable, reliable deployment. 
The tether wire connects to the daughter satellite by the tether attachment subsystem, which securely 
anchors the wire with upper and lower clamp blocks mounted to the 1U frame. The end of the tether wire bends 
around an inside channel between the two clamp blocks, which are then bolted together with M3 bolts to crimp 
the wire and keep it secure. An inline load cell connected between the clamp blocks and mount continuously 
measures tether tension as the wire pulls on the clamp blocks, enabling closed-loop control and ensuring 

6 
operations remain within the material limits and factor of safety requirements. This subsystem transforms the 
daughter satellite into an active component of the deployment and monitoring architecture. 
Because the system can accumulate significant charge as it interacts with the ionosphere, the Talon Tether 
includes a dedicated electron emitter subsystem[6],[7]. This subsystem uses a xenon tank, feed tube, and 
plasma electron emitter capable of producing up to 3 A of electron flux[8]. By expelling electrons from the 
system, the emitter prevents charge buildup, maintains electrical neutrality, and supports electrodynamic 
tether effects in accordance with the mission requirements. 
A critical aspect of the systemвАЩs performance was the selection of the tether wire material. Aluminum 5056-
H18 was chosen due to its excellent balance of high tensile strength, low density, and good electrical 
conductivity, making it ideal for long tether applications where mass efficiency is essential. Aluminum 5056-
H18 also provides strong resistance to fatigue, corrosion, and cold welding which are key concerns for 
conductive materials operating in the microgravity plasma environment of Low Earth Orbit. To enhance 
durability, the wire is coated in Teflon FEP, which provides additional protection against cold welding, atomic 
oxygen erosion, and ultraviolet radiation, ensuring reliable long-duration performance in the harsh LEO 
environment. In addition to the subsystems and tether wire, the product also integrates a comprehensive 
electronics and wiring architecture to support power distribution, motor control, tension monitoring, and 
charge management. The electronics suite consists of a microcontroller, stepper motor controller, load cell 
amplifier, power board, servo driver, and high-voltage converter necessary to energize the electrically powered 
subsystems. 
Combined, these subsystems and components create an integrated solution that meets all key 
requirements of the design brief: controlled deployment of 50вАУ150 m of conductive tether, stable tension 
management, electrostatic charge dissipation, compliance with CubeSat volume and environmental 
constraints, and reliable operation for at least six months in orbit. The Talon Tether provides a robust and flightready architecture that addresses the longstanding need for a safe and functional tether system for small 
satellite missions. 

