2 Technical Background 
The tether deployment system is a mechanical subsystem designed to perform with precision and 
reliability. The system is required to manage tether deployment and retraction while preventing tangling, 
uneven layering, or mechanical failure during operation. The design integrates mechanical and control 
principles to create a compact mechanism capable of operating in Low Earth Orbit (LEO). Developing a system 
like this requires a strong understanding of mechanical design, materials science, and electrodynamic 
principles. 
 Mechanically, many proposed tether missions involve long tethers (kilometers), and the same fundamental 
principles underlie even short-length tether deployment mechanisms like the Talon Tether: controlled payout 
and retraction. Early NASA missions have demonstrated the feasibility of deploying long conductive tethers in 
LEO but also exposed recurring challenges, including maintaining tension, avoiding tangling, and controlling 
electrostatic charge accumulation [3]. These prior missions established that a reliable tether system must 
integrate mechanical, electrical, and control subsystems that are able to operate continuously under variable 
temperature conditions. Designing a reliable tether reel demands knowledge of friction control and 
mechanical synchronization. 
 Another major area of technical background involves the interactions between a conductive tether and the 
surrounding ions in LEO[6]. As the satellites move through space, they collect charged particles that can 
damage the system if not properly managed. Prior research has established the need for a plasma electron 
emitter to maintain safe levels of charge within the system. Understanding this plasma environment is critical 
for integrating these systems into the tether deployment system. 
 Knowledge of space-grade and space-qualified materials is essential for this project. It is necessary for 
materials to withstand extreme fluctuations in temperature for the entire mission duration with line LEO. This 
understanding was critical for material selection throughout the entire system, and especially for the tether 
itself. Together, these areas of technical understanding formed the foundations required to develop the Talon 
TetherвАЩs compact tether deployment mechanism. 

12 
3 Discover Phase: Research 
3.1 Need Statement 
A tether system is needed to connect two 12U satellites with constant tension so they can rotate about 
their common center of mass and generate either lunar or Martian gravity. To enable this mission capability, 
the tether system must fit within a 3U CubeSat volume, deploy up to 150 meters of conductive wire, and 
maintain a stable operating tension throughout deployment and maneuvering. The system must further 
provide electrodynamic charge dissipation, survive launch and LEO environmental conditions, and operate 
autonomously for a minimum of six months without maintenance. 
3.2 5WH Analysis 
The first step of the design process, after identifying the need, was to fully understand the problem. This 
was done through a 5WH analysis with the goals of answering the questions: вАЬWho has the problem?вАЭ, вАЬWhat 
is the problem?вАЭ вАЬWhere is the problem?вАЭ вАЬWhen is the problem?вАЭ вАЬWhy is there a problem?вАЭ, and вАЬHow to fix 
it?вАЭ The table below shows the answers to all these questions as they pertain to the tether system project. 
Table 3.2.1: 5WH Analysis Table for Tether System 
5WH Question Answer 
Who has the problem? Mike Generale and his design team working on the small 
satellite system have the problem to solve. The problem 
affects mission operators and adjacent stakeholders such 
as bus integrators, safety and review boards, launch 
providers, ground segments, and component vendors. 
What is the problem? It is difficult for two satellites in space to maintain stable 
orientation and formation relative to one another due to 
differential orbital mechanics. Satellites need propellant 
to perform orbital maneuvers like changing altitude; 
however, fuel is a finite resource that limits a satelliteвАЩs 
lifespan and the scope of the mission. Extended 
missions require an environment with gravity to 
mitigate the negative effects of microgravity, but 
creating artificial gravity in space is difficult and often 
requires large and complex rotating spacecraft. 
Where is the problem? The problem occurs in low Earth orbit (LEO) where 
there is an abundance of space debris and atmospheric 
drag as well as the presence of microgravity. 
When is the problem? The problem begins during tether deployment where 
maintaining tension and preventing slack is essential. 

13 
Then, over the mission lifetime of at least 6 months, the 
system must withstand orbital thermal cycling, plasma 
interactions, and material degradation. 
Why is there a problem? The problem exists because standard CubeSat buses do 
not include long tether deployment or two-body spin 
control for artificial gravity. Additionally, maintaining 
stable tension is difficult under strict limits of size, mass, 
and power. These challenges are intensified by orbital 
extremes such as thermal cycling, radiation, and plasma 
charging, which can damage materials. Finally, the 
solution needs to ensure reliability, safety, and fault 
recovery over a long mission life. 
How to fix it? A tether system is needed to connect two вАЬ12UвАЭ 
satellites with constant tension to rotate about their 
common center of mass and generate either lunar or 
Martian gravity. 

