From this comparative analysis, several trends emerged. Deployment systems with controlled spooling 
have demonstrated reliability in past missions, while materials offering a balance of strength and 
compactness are critical for meeting volume and load constraints. Conductive options like aluminum and 
copper have been favored for electrodynamic applications, whereas Kevlar and Hoytether designs excel in 
durability. These insights will guide the design direction toward solutions that optimize storage efficiency, 
mechanical strength, and operational simplicity without compromising mission objectives. 

17 
3.5 Kano Model 
A Kano model was developed to sort the projectвАЩs design goals into three categories: Attractive (green), 
Performance (blue), and Basic (red). Attractive features, such as minimizing mass or occupied volume, provide 
disproportionately high client satisfaction the more they are achieved. Performance features like power draw 
and heat dissipation exhibit a linear relationship, meaning improvements directly translate to proportional 
increases in satisfaction. Basic features, including reliability and maintaining constant tension, represent 
fundamental expectations: they must be met for the system to be considered acceptable, but exceeding them 
does not meaningfully increase client satisfaction. This categorization helped the team prioritize design 
decisions based on how each feature contributes to overall client satisfaction. The Kano model used for this 
project is shown in Figure 3.5.1 below. 
Figure 3.5.1: Kano Model of Tether System 

