 After the combination chart was complete, each team member generated a concept sketch using the ideas 
from the above table as a guide. These sketches were done individually to ensure each idea was unique and 
approached solving the problem in a different way. In addition to the concept sketch, each team member wrote 
a brief description of their design in terms of what it consisted of and how it worked. The table below shows 
the nine concept sketches and descriptions generated by each member of the team. 
Table 5.1.2: Design Alternatives Chart for Tether System 
Iteration 1 Design Sketches 
Concept Sketch Description 
Design A: Bryce Addeo Design A for the tether system features a reel and wire 
guide simultaneously driven by a dual motor. Electric 
energy from an external power source enters the motor 
through electronics and jumper wires. The main motor 
converts the electric energy to mechanical energy and 
rotates the spool at a set speed. The rotational motion of 
the second motor is converted to translational motion of 
the wire guide due to the threaded axle it travels along. 
Therefore, the dual motor system rotates the reel and 
translates the wire guide so that there is always an even 
distribution of wire across the spool. The wire goes 
through two rollers on the guide with just enough 
clearance for the wire to nondestructively fit through. This 
ensures a smooth release of the wire while keeping 
appropriate tension. Additionally, these rollers can be 
locked to prevent unwanted release of the tether wire once 
the correct length is achieved. The wire connects to an 
inline load cell on the other end that measures the tension 
in the wire. This load cell features threaded screws on both 
sides to easily attach to the other satellite. The spool has 
large wheel-like sides that sit in grooves in the frame, 
which allows for smooth and secure motion. 

26 
Design B: Sean Raymond Design B features the drum, which holds the tether wound 
in layers and spins on a shaft. A brushless DC motor 
(BLDC) with a field-oriented controller provides smooth, 
precise torque to spin the drum. An encoder mounted on 
the shaft measures rotation for both motor control and 
length estimation. During launch, the drum is locked by a 
pin-puller mechanism that interfaces with the flange of the 
drum, preventing motion under vibration. Once in orbit, 
the pin-puller retracts the pin on command, freeing the 
drum for rotation. To prevent the tether from whipping or 
slapping, two passive brakes ensure smooth payout. A 
spring-loaded friction pad presses against the drum rim, 
providing constant drag, and an eddy-current damper, 
which is an aluminum disk on the shaft with magnets, 
creates speed-proportional drag. At the tether exit, an 
eyelet ensures smooth guidance, an inline load cell 
measures tether tension, and a swivel prevents torsional 
buildup in the tether. 
Design C: Matthew Strogach Design C begins with the mother satellite that houses the 
tether spool, torsional spring, electromagnetic motor, 
actuated pin puller, and slip ring. The other satellite 
contains a housing with a load cell clamp that threads into 
the frame, anchors the tether, measures tension, and sends 
data to the control board to stop the spool when needed. 
The tether passes through a rotary swivel right after the 
mother satellite to prevent twisting as the satellites move 
and rotate. A torsional spring mounted on the spool shaft 
keeps the tether under passive tension, absorbs jerk, and 
stores energy during deployment to help stabilize the 
system. The electromagnetic motor actively controls spool 
rotation once the pin puller is released, regulating speed, 
braking, and reversing if retraction is required. A slip ring 
on the spool shaft transfers electrical power from the 
rotating spool to the CubeSat. A reusable launch lock 
prevents vibration-induced spool movement before 
deployment. The control board powers the motor and 
receives feedback from a shaft encoder that measures 
spool rotations and tether length while also monitoring 
tension from the load cell. During deployment, if tension 
goes too high or too low, the load cell triggers the motor 
to brake. The wiring integrates the motor driver, encoder 
signals, and load cell lines to all electrical systems in the 
design. 
Design D: Wyatt Fritchman Design D for the tether system features a spool driven by 
a motor and a self-locking worm gear mechanism. The 
wiring inside the tether is 30 gauge insulated copper wire, 
which is encased by a protective outer layer. The outer 
layer has both primary and secondary lines to ensure 
protection of the wiring. The tether is wound onto the 

27 
spool, which is fixed to a shaft that can freely rotate. This 
shaft is driven by the motor. The motor drives the spool, 
and a self-locking worm gear stops the tether at the desired 
length and cannot be back-driven due to its high 
mechanical advantage. The motor can reverse the 
direction to bring in the tether at the end of the mission. A 
tachometer is used to determine how much of the tether 
was released. Slip rings on the rotating shaft allow the 
electronics from the CubeSat to connect to the tether 
wiring. All of this is housed inside a 2U frame, with the 
motor, slip ring stator, and tachometer being fixed to the 
frame. The frame is made of aluminum 6061-T6. There is 
an in-line load cell fixed to the second CubeSat and the 
tether which detects the tension in the tether. There are 
more slip rings in the second CubeSat to ensure 
connection, and a tether swivel joint is used to allow for 
the CubeSat to spin without twisting the tether. 
Design E: Joseph Feliciano Design E uses a tether deployment system modeled after a 
level-wind reel, where the main satellite contains a 
motorized spool and level-wind screw that regulate 
winding and unwinding at a controlled rate. The tether 
passes through an eyelet before exiting, reducing angular 
stresses and keeping the line straight. A smaller вАЬanchorвАЭ 
satellite serves as the reaction point and is equipped with 
rod-end bearings to allow free rotation and prevent 
unwanted torsion on the tether. To monitor forces, the 
anchor satellite also includes an inline load cell that 
continuously measures tether tension and sends data back 
to the main satellite. With this feedback, the main satellite 
can automatically adjust the spool speed to maintain 
proper alignment and tension, while the anchor passively 
stabilizes the tether. This configuration ensures smooth 
deployment, accurate tension measurement, and reliable 
control of tether conditions throughout the experiment. 
Design F: Rex Rosenblum Design F utilizes a primary spool that contains the wound 
tether with a direct drive stepper motor with a built-in 
gearbox and a Rotary encoder. At the far end of the spool 
thereвАЩs an electrical slip ring to allow power and signals 
running through the tether to get to the onboard CPU 
without twisting. Near the exit, a rotary encoder attached 
to a friction wheel presses against the tether along with 
two spring loaded friction wheels to get an accurate tether 
length. A bistable mechanism is used as a lock to prevent 
the spool from unreeling during launch and anytime before 
the device is ready to deploy. The system can also be used 

28 
to lock the spool once the desired tether length has been 
reached. A solenoid is used momentarily to switch the 
bistable spool lock on and off and an emergency lock 
bypass is situated near the lock so when a servo is 
actuated, a compressed spring will force the lock open in 
the case of solenoid failure. At the end of the tether, where 
it mounts to the other 12U satellite, there is a slip ring 
paired with an inline load cell to create a closed loop 
system with motor control to maintain appropriate tension. 
Design G: Nick Leger Design G centers around the employment of a direct 
drive motor to drive a worm gear that drives a spur 
gear connected to the spindle. The worm gear utilizes 
a high mechanical advantage so it is inherently selflocking as the worm gear can drive the spur gear, but 
it takes many magnitudes more force for the spur 
gear to drive the worm gear. The wire being used is 
multistrand ribbon cable which means that the cable 
sits uniform and flat in the spindle; this property of 
the cable allows the attached tachometer to calculate 
the length of spindle expended through the rotations 
of the spindle and the Arduino controller. The cable 
attaches to the other cube sat through a slip ring and 
a load cell to both be able to rotate freely to prevent 
kinking or twisting and to be able to calculate the 
tension in the cable. 
Design H: Joel Chung 
Design H consists of three main categories: 
electrical, tether mechanism, and tether control. The 
electrical system consists of power from the tether 
passing through a PCB into an ideal diode Oring FET 
(one-way current control), an SSPC (current limiting 
and fault isolation), and an MPPT (optimizes 
efficiency), before being stored in a supercapacitor 
bank and finally a lithium-ion battery pack. The 

29 
- 
tether mechanism consists of a brushed DC worm 
gear motor that drives the level-wind carriage to 
evenly deploy and retract the tether, housed in an 
aluminum 6061-T6 bracket. The tether control 
system consists of the tether (30 AWG insulated 
copper) being guided through an eyelet with an eddycurrent damper for smooth control, while a solenoidpowered press shoe brake provides a hard stop to 
maintain tension and prevent unwanted movement. 
Design I: Karam Zarnatzi Design I features a compact reel and level-wind assembly 
that can fit in a 2U CubeSat, or potentially a 1U. A stepper 
motor drives the spool, chosen over a BLDC for its 
precision, reliability, and ability to deliver high torque at 
low speeds, with a spring-applied brake mounted on the 
motor shaft acting as a failsafe to lock the spool during 
launch vibrations and automatically engage if power is 
lost. A compound-reverted geartrain connects to the motor 
shaft, providing speed reduction and torque multiplication 
while reducing motor load, and the gearbox drives a 
passive drag element that maintains adjustable baseline 
tension to prevent slack during deployment. This connects 
to the cylindrical tether spool with flanges, while a lead 
screw carriage guides the tether evenly across the reel to 
avoid crossovers and jams. Before exiting the housing, the 
tether passes through a load cell and fairlead, with the load 
cell monitoring tension and enabling adjustment of 
deployment length, and the fairlead reducing stress on the 
tether. At the attachment point to the companion satellite, 
a bearing allows free rotation without torsional loading. 
The design leaves ample space for electronics and sensors, 
with all components communicating to maintain the 
specified baseline. 

30 
5.2 Concept Evaluation 
To successfully determine which of the 9 individual concept sketch drawings would be best suited for 
generation, a selection criteria chart was first developed. This chart consisted of 7 consideration factors that 
were each assigned a different weighted value of importance. The chosen criteria were cost, 
manufacturability, reliability, redundancy, mass/volume, tether release mechanism effectiveness, and proper 
utilization of sensors and electronics. Reliability was selected to have the highest weight in decision-making 
as it dictates and determines the designвАЩs ability to perform without failure. The selection criteria table (Table 
5.2.1) would serve as a baseline for choosing the best design concept sketch. 
Table 5.2.1: Selection Criteria Table 
Selection Criterion Weight Description
Cost 12.5% The price of raw materials, off the shelf components 
and manufacturing. 
Manufacturability 17.5% Considers both the number and complexity of parts, 
fasteners, sub-mechanisms and manufacturing 
time. 
Reliability 25% Considers the designвАЩs ability to perform without 
failure. 
Redundancy 5% The ability of the system to fail and continue 
performance with backup components. 
Mass/Volume 20% Considers how much it weighs and how much space 
it takes up (1U, 2U, 3U, etc.). 
Tether Release 
Mechanism Effectiveness 
15% Considers the effectiveness/efficiency of the 
mechanism responsible for retracting/deploying the 
tether. This includes locking, maintaining tension, 
distribution of wire on the reel, and the ability to 
retract. 
Proper Utilization of Sensors and 
Electronics 
5% Considers how well thought-out the configuration of 
sensors and electronics is. This includes specific 
names and functions for sensor/electronics and 
proper power flow. 
After the creation of this table, a Pugh Chart (Table 5.2.2) was then developed. In this chart, one of the 
concept sketches created was chosen to serve as a reference to the other designs. The reference sketch was 
selected based on group discussion and client needs, determining that Design B would serve as a strong 
middle-ground design. Using factors from the selection criteria, each of the concepts was ranked against 
Design B and scored to determine the best one. Using each of the selection criteria, a plus symbol was used 
to determine if a selection criterion in a design was better than the one in Design B. A minus sign was used if a 
design ranked worse in each selection criterion than in Design B. Finally, a zero was entered if both designs 

31 
were determined to be equal in following the assigned selection criteria. A plus symbol would correspond to 1 
point, a minus symbol would subtract a point, and a zero would change nothing. The rankings were assigned 
based on group discussion and deliberation in addition to client needs and the weighting of each selection 
criteria. After each design was compared, the pluses and minuses were combined to determine final point 
values. This chart would not only allow for determination of the best design concept, but it also allowed for an 
analysis of which designs were strongest in certain selection criteria. This would be valuable for possible 
combinations of design concepts in the final CAD model. 
Table 5.2.2: Design Concept Pugh Chart 
After the chart was completed and the final points were determined, the four designs with the highest 
scores were selected to move forward into a decision matrix. The designs with the highest scores were 
concepts B, D, F, and G, with concept F having the highest ranking with a net total of 1 point. The decision 
matrix (Table 5.2.3) was used to score the four highest-ranked concepts by ranking each of the selection 
criteria for each concept on a scale of 1-10. The weight assignments of each selection criteria were 
incorporated to create a final average for each of the four designs out of 10. To determine these ranking 
assignments, another round of group deliberation was completed for each selection criteria in each of the 
individual designs. Decisions were also made based on client needs. 

32 
Table 5.2.3: Design Concept Decision Matrix 
After the decision matrix was completed, Design F had the highest total rating of 6.55, proving to be the best 
design concept. This design had much better redundancy, reliability, and excellent proper utilization of 
sensors and electronics compared to the other concepts. Its detailed wiring system would provide a strong 
basis for CAD modeling of the final product. Its simplicity would serve well in the actual creation of the model. 
The only criteria that design F ranked lower in was cost from the complicated wiring system and mass, and 
volume. However, the cost did not rank significantly lower than the other designs, and mass and volume 
produced a lower ranking for all four of the concepts. However, mass and volume only had a 5% weighting 
value; therefore was not a very effective factor in making the final decision. Design F would serve as the best 
selected concept and would be used for CAD modeling, while strong parts from other concepts may be used 
as well to output the best overall design. 

33 
6 Deliver Phase: Final Design Concept 
6.1 Product Assembly and Systems 
The final design concept shown in Figure 6.1.1 below incorporates a larger 3U frame for installation into the 
mother satellite and a smaller 1U frame for attachment to the daughter satellite. Starting at the top right of the 
3U frame and rotating counterclockwise, the design features a motor, a reel subsystem, a microservo reel lock, 
and a level wind subsystem. Moving to the 1U frame, there is the tether attachment subsystem and the 
electron emitter subsystem. Finally, there is the tether wire that connects the two frames together, and a box 
representing where the CPU and electronics would go in the 3U frame. The reel subsystem is the main system 
that contains the tether wire and has locking capabilities to ensure no accidental unspooling during launch. 
The reel has a geared connection with the level wind subsystem to allow for orderly tether spooling without 
additional motors. 
Figure 6.1.1: Full Design Assembly with Important Components and Subsystems Labeled 
The reel subsystem displayed in Figure 6.1.2 below is comprised of a main spool, mounts on either side, a 
supporting ball bearing, and a drive motor. The addition of a small servo motor attached to the left reel mount 
adds locking capabilities to the system as well. The stepper motor used has a built-in gearbox that ends with a 
D profile output shaft that meshes with a cutout in the side of the spool, allowing for power transfer. The motor 
uses four screws to mount rigidly to the right reel mount and acts as a bearing for the spool. On the left, the 
spool uses a ball bearing supported by the left reel mount to increase reliability, decrease wear, and ensure 
smooth spool rotation. An M5 screw threads into the gear end of the spool and acts as an anchor point for the 
end of the tether wire that feeds through the small 5-millimeter hole drilled radially into the spool. Wrapping 
the end of the tether wire around this screw ensures the tether remains attached to the spool even at full 
extension. Finally, a micro servo motor mounts to the left reel mount with two M2 bolts and, when actuated, 
acts as a physical interlock to the built-in gear on the spool. 

34 
Figure 6.1.2: Exploded View of Reel Subsystem with Labeled Components
The level wind subsystem shown in Figure 6.1.3 below mounts directly in front of the previously mentioned 
reel subsystem and is responsible for maintaining even and orderly spooling and unspooling of the tether. The 
main component is the bidirectional threaded rod that the carriage rides back and forth on. The threaded rod 
is supported on both ends by bearings that are mounted to the 3U frame via bearing mounts and M3 screws. A 
second, smooth rod lies below the threaded rod and runs through a clearance hole in the carriage, preventing 
any twisting. Finally, at the far end of the threaded rod, there is a drive gear that meshes with the gear on the 
reel subsystem and is held in place using an alignment key and E-clip. 
Figure 6.1.3: Sectional View of Level Wind Subsystem with Labeled Components 

35 
 The tether attachment subsystem in Figure 6.1.4 below is one of two main systems in the 1U daughter 
satellite. A triangular mount is fastened to the 1U frame via four M3 bolts, and a clearance hole on the vertical 
face acts as a mounting point for the load cell. A lock nut threads onto one end of the load cell, connecting it 
to the mount. The other end of the load cell threads into the lower clamp block in the rear, and the upper clamp 
block screws down onto that. Before torquing the screws, the tether is fed into the slot and, upon tightening, 
is securely fastened to the clamping block assembly. Due to the direct connection from the tether to one end 
of the load cell and the other end being stationary, any tension in the tether will be accurately measured with 
the load cell. Tension data is read by a small onboard computer, and the results are fed to the larger satellite's 
computer for transmission. 
Figure 63.1.4: Isometric and Section View of Tether Attachment Subsystem with Labeled Components 
 Finally, the electron emitter subassembly shown in Figure 6.1.5 is comprised of an off-the-shelf electron 
emitter and mount which is designed to emit up to 3 Amps. A gas tube connects the electron emitter to a xenon 
tank which is held in place with its own mount. The same small onboard computer used for the load cell also 
monitors static build up and actuates the electron emitter as needed to dissipate charge. The chosen electron 
emitter relies on high voltage which comes from its controller to ionize the on-board xenon gas to create 
plasma. Plasma is highly conductive due to the excess number of electrons, so the plasma вАЬbeamвАЭ created by 
the electron emitter effectively creates a wire that connects the satellite to the surrounding space with a lower 
potential allowing for current to flow. Overall, the electron emitter ensures that excessive static charge is 
dispelled into space to keep the entire system grounded [12]. 

36 
Figure 6.1.5: Isometric View of Electron Emitter Subsystem with Labeled Components 

37 
