Maximum Expected Tether Tension 
To verify that the selected tether material and diameter satisfy the structural requirements of the mission, 
the tension in the tether was evaluated using a free-body diagram (FBD) in the deployed configuration. The 
tether was modeled as a flexible member transmitting axial force between the daughter and mother satellites. 
External forces acting on the system include a gravitational gradient, relative orbital motion, and the restoring 
force generated by the reel assembly. For sizing the tether, the dominant load was assumed to be the 
centripetal force required to maintain the daughter satellite at its maximum deployed radius of 150 meters. 
Dynamic effects, such as oscillations and transient deployment loads, were treated separately using safety 
factors. Due to the exact mass of each satellite being unknown, with the client providing 24 kg as an estimate, 
the tether was designed under the worst-case assumption that the mother satellite would be 50% heavier than 
the daughter satellite. 
Figure 7.1.4: Free Body Diagram of The Tether 
First, NewtonвАЩs second law was applied in the radial direction. The tether force was assumed to act along 
the center of mass of both satellites, and the satelliteвАЩs motion was approximated as circular relative to the 
system center of mass. The required tether tension is therefore given by the mass of the daughter satellite 
multiplied by its radial acceleration. Additional contributions from the mass of the tether itself were included 
as secondary terms using the same methodology. 
Figure 7.1.5: Satellite System Model 

45 
After deriving the general tension expression, numerical values corresponding to the system geometry, 
satellite mass, and deployment radius were substituted. A factor of safety consistent with the Product Design 
Specifications was applied to account for uncertainties in loading, manufacturing variability, and 
environmental degradation throughout the six-month mission in low Earth orbit. The resulting required 
minimum breaking load was then compared to the tensile capacity of aluminum 5056 wire for the selected 
diameter. 
