Tether Material Selection 
To establish the allowable material density for the tether, a maximum system mass of 2.5 kg, a total tether 
length of 155 m, and a wire diameter of 2.05 mm were used. These constraints yield a maximum permissible 
density of approximately 4886 kg/m¬≥ for the tether material. In addition to mass limitations, the material is 
required to withstand temperatures up to at least 120 ¬∞C and as low as вИТ150 ¬∞C while maintaining adequate 
electrical conductivity for system operation. With these mechanical, thermal, and electrical constraints 
defined, a tensile-strength-versus-density plot was generated in Ansys Granta to identify candidate materials 
that satisfy both the mass limit and the required environmental performance. 
Figure 7.1.6: ANSYS Tether Material Density Vs. рЭЭИрЭТЪ Plot 

47 
For the tether, the constraints called for something light, strong, conductive, and stable in LEO 
temperatures without embrittlement. That mostly limited possibilities to aluminum-based alloys. Within the 
aluminum family, the 5000 series is ideal because the magnesium alloying provides strain hardening and 
environmental resistance. 5056 was selected specifically because it has one of the highest yield strengths in 
the 5000s family, and itвАЩs commonly used for high-strength wire rope. 
