7.2 Design Prototyping 
The initial design prototype was created entirely in CAD, then the necessary files were converted to STL 
mesh files for 3D printing. All OTS parts were ordered from vendors, and custom parts were printed via FDM 
3D printing technology. 3D printing can be a very useful tool for confirming fitment and assembly; however, 
there are limitations that need to be considered. Some parts needed to be temporarily modified from the final 
design to allow for 3D printing so that other interfaces could still be checked. 
Unlike the final design, all mounts were merged with the floor of the satellite into one body for ease of 
prototype assembly and to reduce the need for additional fasteners. Also, the OTS motor was not available 
easily, so a custom hand crank part was created to take the place of the motor and allow for spool rotation. 
The bidirectional threaded rod proved to be a challenge to replicate, as the final part would be 
manufactured on a precision lathe out of metal, and printing a fine threaded rod is a challenge for FDM 3D 
printing. This required that a simplified version of the threaded rod be created to allow for fitment and 
movement checks despite the thread pitch not being accurate to the final design. In addition to this, the only 
reliable way to print a thin and strong threaded rod is to split it in half and print both halves separately. Both 
halves can be glued together after printing, but with the tolerances of 3D printing, this can sometimes lead to 
an imperfect thread and coarse movement. Despite these challenges, the prototype was assembled with an 
accurate appearance to the CAD model as shown in figure 7.2.1 below. 
Figure 7.2.1: Prototype of Talon Tether System 
Instead of the selected Aluminum 5056-H18 tether wire, string was used in this prototype to connect the 
two frames together. As previously stated, all custom components were 3D printed as seen by the white 
material, while all OTS parts were accurate to what would be used in the real product. The prototype worked 

52 
as intended except for the level wind subsystem. The carriage was not meshing well with the double threaded 
rod which prevented it from translating as the spool rotated. This was due to the limited dimensional accuracy 
that came with using a 3D printer for a part that needed to have high precision and accuracy to properly 
function. Overall, the prototyping process confirmed that the design was structurally sound and functioned as 
intended, and that the double threaded rod and carriage of the level wind would be the most difficult custom 
parts to manufacture, requiring high dimensional accuracy and precision.

53 
8 Deliver Phase: Design for X 
8.1 Design for Reliability 
Ensuring the tether deployment system performs reliably under all conditions requires identifying where 
potential weaknesses may occur and addressing them early in the design phase. The DFMEA process serves 
this purpose by systematically examining each subsystem, predicting possible failure modes, and evaluating 
their consequences on overall mission performance. For this analysis, the tether system was divided into its 
main components: the tether root clamp and spool assembly, motor and bearing supports, level-wind 
mechanism and gears, emergency brake system, electronics and control hardware, tether outlet and wiring, 
inline load cell and clamp block, and the electron emitter subsystem. Each component was analyzed for how 
it could fail, why those failures might occur, and what effects they would have on system operation. Table 8.1.1 
presents the results of this evaluation, detailing each failure mode along with its cause, effect, and ranking 
according to four key criteria: Severity (S), Occurrence (O), Detection (D), and the Risk Priority, which are all 
defined below. 
1. Severity (S): Rates the seriousness of the effect of a failure on system performance on a scale from 1 
(no effect) to 10 (catastrophic failure or mission loss). 
2. Occurrence (O): Estimates the likelihood that a specific failure will happen, rated from 1 (rare or 
unlikely) to 10 (highly probable or frequent). 
3. Detection (D): Measures the ability to detect a failure before it causes harm, scored from 1 (easily 
detected) to 10 (undetectable before failure). 
4. Risk Priority Number (RPN): A calculated value determined by RPN = S √Ч O √Ч D, used to prioritize 
failure modes by combining their severity, likelihood, and detectability. 
