8.2 Design for Environmental Factors 
Because the satellite system will be subject to harsh environmental conditions, whether during launch or 
while orbiting Earth, designing a system that can not only withstand but also perform at a high level is an 
integral consideration when prototyping and implementing the design. 
 Considering launch initially, the satellite must be able to withstand acceleration loads, such as lateral gвАЩs, 
during launch as well as random vibrations. As the satellite is launched, it will shake violently. Structural and 
non-structural parts in the tether system must avoid loosening, cracking, or failure via random vibration. 
Acoustic-induced stress is also a useful consideration because when the rocket is launching, engines and 
airflow create high sound pressure that can shake, vibrate, and damage delicate parts. During rocket 
separation, a phenomenon called pyro shock occurs when explosive bolts or springs create a strong, quick 
shock wave, causing a massive force equivalent to thousands of gвАЩs. Circuit boards and connectors in the 
tether system are especially at risk of being damaged or failing due to pyro shock. 
 As the system approaches low Earth orbit, new, harsh environmental factors come into play. Atomic oxygen 
aggressively erodes polymers/coatings and roughens surfaces; rapid dayвАУnight thermal cycling (вЙИ вИТ120 ¬∞C to 
+120 ¬∞C) drives fatigue, CTE-mismatch stress, and tether length changes; trapped radiation (TID/SEE) 
degrades electronics; the ionospheric plasma causes surface charging, arcing risk, and EMI/EMC issues, 
especially around long conductors like tethers. Free-molecular aerodynamic drag is significant and variable 
with solar activity, affecting attitude, tether tension, and orbit decay. Micrometeoroid-and-debris (MMOD) 
impacts threaten thin structures and lines, motivating multi-filament or shielded designs. UV darkening and 
AO together accelerate material aging. Finally, EarthвАЩs magnetic field interacts with currents in long 
conductors, inducing voltages/torques (useful for electrodynamic tethers but also a control and power-budget 
driver). Designing for LEO means choosing AO/UV-resistant materials, controlling charging paths, sizing 
thermal control and drag margins, and verifying MMOD tolerance and end-of-life performance. 
Upon re-entry of EarthвАЩs atmosphere after the 6-month lifespan of the satellite system, the remnants of the 
satellite system will land at Point Nemo, a remote section of sea in the South Pacific Ocean. The tether system 
is constructed from non-hazardous and non-poisonous materials to mitigate the risk of polluting the ocean 
environment where the satellite will land. 

57 
8.3 Design for Maintainability 
Unfortunately, in-orbit repair is not possible, so it is critical to focus on ease of assembly/disassembly and 
making sure the mechanical components are properly maintained. It is also important to account for 
maintainability in failure modes and ground maintainability before launch. While those aspects are the most 
essential, there are many other factors that need to be accounted for. Fortunately, the tether deployment 
system was designed with maintainability in mind to simplify ground assembly, integration, and testing prior 
to launch. The design utilizes standardized fasteners, labeled quick-disconnects, and accessible mounting 
points to ensure that tools can reach critical areas and that parts can be replaced or adjusted with minimal 
disassembly. The inclusion of a ball bearing support and a detachable spool mount facilitates easy 
replacement of wear-prone components, while consistent use of mechanical interfaces such as alignment 
pins and standardized screw types minimizes reassembly errors. Electrical connections for the stepper motor, 
servo brake, and load cell are routed through organized harnesses with labeled connectors to streamline 
inspection and diagnostics. 
The table below lists which parts can be removed and replaced relatively easily if needed during 
testing/prototyping. While every part is removable, the ones labelled вАЬNoвАЭ indicate that they would require 
the removal of several other parts to get to. The last column lists whether a part is off the shelf (OTS). 
