8.4 Design for Economic Factors 
The design of the tether system has been developed with consideration of economic factors that influence 
both material selection and manufacturability. While the system is primarily driven by functional and 
performance requirements rather than consumer market dynamics, economic considerations remain critical 
to ensure cost-effectiveness and feasibility within the context of academic and small satellite missions. 
The use of standardized CubeSat architectures, specifically a 3U frame to fit within the primary satellite 
and a 1U frame for the secondary unit, provides significant economic advantages. This configuration leverages 
the well-established CubeSat ecosystem, which reduces development and integration costs by enabling 
compatibility with standardized deployment systems and allowing for less development in integrating the 
tether system with the rest of the satellite. 
Material selection was guided by a balance between performance, cost, and manufacturability. Aluminum 
was chosen for the primary structural elements, including mounts, gears, and the spool, due to its favorable 
strength-to-weight ratio, ease of machining, and cost efficiency. Stainless steel is utilized selectively for small, 
high-stress components such as the reel lock mechanism to ensure reliability without incurring excessive 
material expenses. 
The incorporation of stepper and servo motors, both widely available and cost-effective components, 
further supports economic sustainability. These mass-produced parts offer consistent performance at low 
cost while simplifying sourcing and maintenance. Additionally, the modular design of the tether deployment 
system featuring a spool, level-wind mechanism, and integrated electronics on a hardware faceted mounting 
system within the CubeSats facilitates streamlined assembly, scalability, and potential reusability in future 
iterations. 
Although the tether system is not directly affected by fluctuations in consumer economic systems, it is 
indirectly influenced by global supply chain conditions within the aerospace and electronics sectors. The 
availability and pricing of components such as xenon tanks and electron emitters may vary based on 
manufacturing trends, material costs, and technological development. To mitigate these risks, the design 
emphasizes the use of more standardized, readily available components that can be substituted with 
equivalent alternatives, if necessary, rather than custom-built parts. 
In conclusion, while the design of the tether system is primarily governed by technical and operational 
requirements, careful consideration has been given to economic factors to ensure the system remains costefficient, manufacturable, and sustainable within the financial constraints typical of small satellite missions. 

60 
8.5 Ethical Considerations 
All the design engineers involved in this project adhered to the standards of the American Society of 
Mechanical Engineers (ASME) Code of Ethics of Engineers, including the 10 fundamental canons. The 
fundamental principles of this document are the following: 
Engineers uphold and advance the integrity, honor, and dignity of the engineering profession by: 
I. using their knowledge and skill for the enhancement of human welfare; 
II. being honest and impartial, and serving with fidelity their clients (including their employers) and 
the public; and 
III. striving to increase the competence and prestige of the engineering profession. 
This tether system is designed to comply with international space regulations to minimize the risk of 
generating space debris. Each component and subsystem (spool, level wind, ceramic outlet, emergency 
brake, etc.) was designed to prevent fragmentation or an uncontrolled, dragging tether. Materials were used to 
avoid shedding, sharp-edge abrasion of the wire, and hazardous ground test practices, as well as to ensure 
long-term durability. Additionally, components such as the emergency brake system were integrated into the 
system to provide redundancy. There are no conflicts of interest between the design team and the international 
space regulations. 

61 
