74 
10 Discussion and Conclusion 
The final design satisfies the majority of the Product Design Specifications established during the define 
phase. All dimensional and mass requirements were met, with the assembly fitting within the designated 
CubeSat envelope and remaining below the allowable system weight. Structural requirements were achieved 
through the selection of aluminum 5056 for the tether and 6061-T6 for the mounting components, both of 
which provide sufficient strength, stiffness, and environmental durability for a six-month mission in low Earth 
orbit. The tether system meets the specified minimum factor of safety in tension, and the overall geometry of 
the structure analytically withstands launch and tether loads. 
Performance specifications were also met. The chosen stepper motor exceeded initial power 
requirements, but an agreement was reached with the requirement to allocate enough power to allow the 
function of the design. Preliminary thermal analysis indicates that heat generation remains within acceptable 
bounds. The constant-tension requirement was addressed through the selected drive configuration; while full 
validation would require further testing, analytical results indicate achievement of tether and reel subsystem 
PDS criteria. Aesthetics and manufacturability goals were supported by using simple planar components, 
standard welds, and a minimal number of custom parts. 
Usability and installation requirements were satisfied by keeping the assembly straightforward to 
manufacture and assemble, with fasteners and welds positioned for clear access. Environmental 
requirements, including microgravity survivability, vacuum compatibility, and material behavior under thermal 
cycling, were met through appropriate material selection and the use of space-rated coating and insulation 
strategies. 
A few specifications remain partially validated rather than fully demonstrated. Electrical insulation 
performance and long-term wear of the tether coating would benefit from extended testing. Similarly, the 
bending behavior of the tether around the guide features is analytically acceptable but would require physical 
testing to fully confirm long-term use. These limitations do not represent failures to meet the PDS but rather 
areas where experimental verification was outside the scope of the project. Overall, the design meets all 
essential PDS criteria, with further testing required to fully validate some structural, vibrational, and thermal 
claims. 

